A Snail’s Path — What is Success?

The vine is higher than the sky,
The leaves are too large for my eye.
Inching slowly with each step I take,
My shell exacerbating my body’s ache.

If I let go, the pain would stop,
But if I capitulate, I won’t see the top.
Never to drink the dew on the leaves,
Never to glimpse what I may achieve. 

And so, I keep going,
Gradually, I keep climbing.
One branch at a time,
Leaving behind my slime. 

Maybe, one day I’ll finally make it,
Because no matter what, I won’t quit.
As long as the sun keeps shining,
I know that I will keep trying.

Perhaps I’ll never reach the top,
But that doesn’t mean I’ll ever stop.
Even if the world thinks I’ve failed,
If I persevere I’ll have success nailed.

As an avid lover of mathematics, I have always been mesmerized by both the beauty of math but also the potential in its applications. Growing up, my father always told me that everything in our universe — whether it be the plants around us or the stars in the sky — could all be described using mathematics. When I was young, I didn't truly comprehend the meaning behind his words, but with the passing of time, I began to dive deeper into the art of problem-solving. Soon, I developed a deepened love and appreciation for perhaps the most simple yet complicated language in the world: the language of mathematics. A short equation, a simple model, from Euler's Formula to the Gold Ratio, mathematics has the power to say so much in so little.

Yet over time, I began to be captivated by the infinite applications and possibilities of math. Needless to say, math on its own is a beauty to behold, but when combined with other subjects like physics and biology, it has the power to change the world. My undeniable passion and solid foundation in mathematics greatly strengthen my qualifications as a candidate for COSMOS as math serves as the cornerstone for so many other fields of STEM.

My qualifications expand beyond my capabilities in terms of math and STEM — my strong communication and presentation skills will empower me to draw the entire community of my cluster closer together. My experience on my high school speech team has guided me to find my voice and uncover my confidence. This year, I placed first in Declamation at National Catholic Forensic League Qualifications. Even though the program will be held virtually this year, I know that my outgoing and optimistic personality will enhance the experience of everyone in my cluster.

Curiosity, with its ability to change the world, is perhaps one of the most important traits in humans. As a student, I have always been the one to continuously ask my science teachers the driving question of "why?" And much this "why" that I am looking for can be answered through physics. A science that strives to understand how our universe behaves satisfies my neverending search of understanding how the world around me pieces together.
Taking AP Statistics this year has opened for me, a new door of possibilities. It has introduced a world where using data and observations, we can extrapolate from what we know and expand into the future, we can use small samples to reach conclusions on large populations. As the course progressed, I began to nurture ever-growing respect and admiration for data and its infinite possibilities. Despite not having a solid understanding of Big Data and Machine Learning, the courses I have taken and the knowledge I have gained over time have compelled me to dive deeper into this field of science that has the ability to completely change the world around us. I wish to embark on this never-ending journey of knowledge starting at COSMOS.

The Perfect Poem

I have been searching,
In agony, for the perfect poem.
A poem that says it all — 
All my sorrows, all my joys.
The words that paint the picture
None but my heart can see.
A poem that lives, that reaches,
Beyond what I can.

But I never seem to see,
The destination of my journey.
Always out of reach, always out of touch.
I extend my hand,
Only to catch empty feathers. 
The words I cast, the paint that drops,
Everything falls into the wrong spot.

But can you see,
My toilsome search, 
For that of which I may never uncover. 
An undying want,
To rip open my heart for the world to see.
Yet what would it see?
My tears, my laughter? 
The words time has taken away —
Or what it has failed to steal?

Perhaps this journey,
This endless, beautiful journey,
Is my poem.
My struggles the words, my love the paint,
Perfection woven only in imperfection.
My tainted life, my perfect poem.
